result.execSummary:
The defendant Donald J. Seis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Donald J. Seis is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Donald J. Seis was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Donald J. Seis in court with attorney Daniel Terry Cveykus.  Ralph Malcom Uttke appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called @ 9:38 a.m. Agreement stated - State amends ct 1 to 947.01(1) misd DC, ct 2 dismiss, withheld sentence, 1 yr probation, counseling, court costs, no contact with victims, their daughter or their home. State has complied with victim notification requirements. Victims wish to be heard. Atty Cveykus and Def agree. Court reviews plea quest. Court grants amendment. Plea to amended ct 1 - no contest. Constitutional rights, elements, possible penalties reviewed. Ct 2 dismissed. Atty Cveykus satisfied. Court finds Def understands and plea freely & voluntarily made. Factual basis stipulated. Court accepts plea and finds guilty of ct 1 disorderly conduct. Statement by S.W. Sentencing remarks by Counsel. Nothing by Defendant. Court addresses questions raised by victim. Court approves agreement. Sentence withheld, 1 yr probation, counseling, AODA, court costs, apply bond, credit for 1 day if revoked, no contact with victims or their daughters or their property. DNA sample and surcharge. DNA colloquy.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered, without further order of the court, against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. Postconviction rights.
